docs/devlog/detailed/2026-04-26_2026-04-26.md-66-- **H2 — Layer sparsity hole (Codex + Gemini High, two-reviewer consensus):** `setCell` / `setAt` / `fill` now compare incoming value against `defaultValue` and `cells.delete(idx)` on match (instead of storing a marker entry). `fill(defaultValue)` short-circuits to `cells.clear()`. The in-memory map and the `getState` output now stay in sync without a round-trip. Equality test: strict `===` for primitive `T`, `jsonFingerprint` comparison for object `T`.
docs/devlog/detailed/2026-04-26_2026-04-26.md-67-- **H4 — Layer unbounded `structuredClone` (Gemini High):** constructor now caches `_isPrimitive = isImmutablePrimitive(defaultValue)` (true for `number | string | boolean | null`). Every read/write boundary checks `_isPrimitive` and skips `structuredClone` when true — primitives are immutable on the JS side, so the defensive-copy contract is structurally satisfied without the call. `Layer<number>` etc. are now zero-allocation across reads and writes. Object `T` paths are unchanged.
docs/devlog/detailed/2026-04-26_2026-04-26.md:68:- **L5 — `clear`/`clearAt` (Opus Low, falls out of H2):** added explicit "drop this cell back to default" methods. Idempotent on already-default cells. Bounds-validated.
docs/devlog/detailed/2026-04-26_2026-04-26.md-69-- **M4 — `Layer.fromState` double-validate (Opus Medium):** `assertJsonCompatible(value)` was being called explicitly per cell, then `jsonFingerprint(value)` was called, and `jsonFingerprint`'s implementation calls `assertJsonCompatible` itself — paying validation twice. Removed the explicit call. `fromState` now validates each value once.
docs/devlog/detailed/2026-04-26_2026-04-26.md-70-- **M5 — `Layer.clone` double-clone (Gemini Medium):** `clone()` was implemented as `Layer.fromState(this.getState())` — two `structuredClone` passes per cell plus an intermediate `LayerState` allocation. Now implemented directly: instantiate a new layer with the same options, iterate `this.cells` once, single clone per entry (or no clone for primitive `T`).
docs/devlog/detailed/2026-04-26_2026-04-26.md:71:- **Bonus** `forEachReadOnly(cb)` — added as the explicit zero-allocation traversal path for object `T` consumers who own the no-mutate discipline. Documented in api-reference. Existing `forEach` keeps its safe-clone semantics.
